english:
  title: A Parting Gift for the Venerable Monk Yuan
  author: Lee Suk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I first met the Venerable One upon a boat on the Yang River. Clean and refined in bearing, with the air of one devoted to the Way, I felt at once the warmth of an old friendship rekindled. As the narrow waters obstructed our passage, sometimes we pushed the vessel forward, sometimes we pulled it through—laborious work that would have tried any man's patience. Yet he never showed a sign of reluctance. At first I thought this mere forbearance, but as the days wore on without the slightest flagging of effort, I came to understand: here was a man of true aspiration. In those remaining days, still possessed of surplus strength, we pursued the coolness into the river itself. There the boat was drawn through the water, his robes clinging wet to his skin, while those around us pointed and laughed. The Venerable One remained unmoved. Not merely a man of determination, but one who has transcended the tyranny of form itself.

    Those who enter the Way are like horses freed from the yoke—unbounded in their galloping, without fixed direction. Only when one is no longer enslaved by material desire can one truly sit while sitting, walk while walking, standing tall in self-mastery, and finally move with complete autonomy. The Venerable One seems to approach this state.

    One day he said to me, "I am about to journey through distant lands. Will you not offer me words of parting?" I replied, "What you seek is not what I have learned, and what I have learned is not what you seek. What words can I offer? Yet the ancients spoke of friendship formed from but half a glance. How much more should I not speak, having shared a boat and its deeper bonds? So I do not refuse, but set down these rough words as my gift.

    The Venerable's name is Jing-yuan. He transmits the teachings of the Flower Garland Sutra and now goes to join the wandering cloud-monks of the Southern School. I know well that his worth far exceeds the price of a pair of grass sandals.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Yang River' (楊州) refers to the region around present-day Yangzhou, a major trading center in medieval China.
    - '''Freed from the yoke'' (泛駕之馬) is a Buddhist metaphor for liberation from worldly constraints and the illusion of fixed identity.'
    - '''Cloud-water monks'' (雲水僧) refers to itinerant Buddhist monks who wander from place to place in search of spiritual enlightenment.'
    - The reference to 'grass sandals' (草鞋錢) alludes to the minimal material support a wandering monk requires, suggesting the Venerable One's spiritual wealth transcends material measure.
